entry.summary:
I’ve been building an application with Laravel 8.0 recently that utilizes a lot of console commands for various housekeeping reasons. For most of these methods, I want to utilize a dry-run test to deny changes by default.
The first most obvious approach is to use an option that you can check in each of your function calls. That would look like:
public function myMethod() {
    if ($this->dryrun) {
        return;
    }

    // Execute destructive code...
}

This puts a little too much pressure on each function to know about what a dry-run even is, how to check against it, and it couples logic too directly.
The approach I’ve chosen to use instead utilizes PHP’s magic __call() to help make better determinations; much of Laravel uses this as well.
